  "name": "Indian Classical Dance: Natya — The Fifth Veda",
  "description": "The Natyashastra, attributed to Bharata Muni (~200 BCE), is sometimes called the Fifth Veda — a scripture of embodied knowledge where every gesture is a word, every expression a sentence, every dance a prayer. This grammar maps the nine rasas (emotional essences), the hand mudras (gesture vocabulary), the eight classical dance forms, and the repertoire structure — from the opening Alarippu to the devotional Padam. A living tradition spanning two millennia, performed today by millions.\n\nPUBLIC DOMAIN ILLUSTRATION REFERENCES: Illustrations from early translations of the Natyashastra. Bronze Chola dynasty Nataraja sculptures (10th-12th century). Tanjore paintings of dancers (18th-19th century). Ajanta cave murals depicting dance postures (2nd century BCE - 6th century CE).",
  "grammar_type": "custom",
  "creator_name": "PlayfulProcess",
  "tags": ["dance", "india", "embodiment", "sacred", "natyashastra", "rasa", "mudra", "classical", "devotion"],
  "roots": ["eastern-wisdom", "embodiment", "myth-and-symbol"],
  "shelves": ["wisdom", "wonder"],
  "lineages": ["Shrei", "Akomolafe"],
  "worldview": "devotional",
  "grammars": [
